data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 9 (`.NET 9`), the Cosmos DB provider began **blocking synchronous query/save operations by default**, but offered the `EnableSyncOverAsync()` opt-in as a migration aid. In EF Core 11 (`.NET 11`), **that opt-in is removed entirely**. All your synchronous calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no configuration workaround.

### Affected methods in your code

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(…)` | `.FirstAsync(…)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods — async propagates up the call stack.
- `Add()` remains synchronous (it only tracks in memory); no change needed there.
- Remove any `EnableSyncOverAsync()` configuration — it will fail to compile in EF Core 11.
